RileyCountyPD
August 21 at 2:00 PM ·

With school starting next week for Manhattan-Ogden USD 383, Riley County Grade School, Riley County High School, and Blue Valley we want to remind citizens of some school zone safety tips.

🚗Slow down for school speed zones in the morning and afternoon.

🛑Stop for school buses and recognize their stop signs, do not go around the bus, it is a major safety issue with our kids, especially the small ones.
🚙 All lanes traveling both directions on the roadway must stop!

❌ No cell phones or texting while driving

Our officers will be doing enhanced traffic enforcement in school zones throughout Riley County over the next few weeks.

post_text: Today we celebrated the groundbreaking for the renovations and additions to Manhattan High School! Construction recently began behind the building. There will be an additional gymnasium, new tennis courts, two additional parking lots and practice field for athletics and marching band. The front addition will start in 2021. The full project is scheduled to be completed in August of 2022.

post_text:
As you may know, the Kansas State Board of Education voted against Governor Kelly's Executive Order to delay the start of school until September 9th. We understand that this leaves our community with a lot of concerns and questions.

The district administration will discuss what this means for USD 383 and will provide our community with more information soon.

We want to thank our families, staff, and community for your ongoing patience during this whole process. We know how difficult these several months have been for many in the USD 383 family. Please watch our social media pages and our website for updates.

RileyCountyPD
July 16 at 5:19 PM ·

SCAM ALERT:
Multiple citizens and businesses have reported a scammer calling and claiming to be a fundraising entity raising funds for the USD 383: Manhattan High School Football and Cheerleading teams. The caller will mention Coach Tenbrink or Coach Schartz and ask for a donation to be made to the team.

Do Not provide personal information or payment by phone. This caller does not represent a fundraiser for the local High School teams. To verify any fundraiser before providing payment you can call the Manhattan High School at (785) 587-2100 and ask to speak with Athletic Director Mike Marsh.

Talk to your friends, family and neighbors about the scams going around to stay aware. You can always contact RCPD if you are suspicious of the situation at (785) 537-2112.

Happy Juneteenth! On June, 19, 1865 Union General Gordon Granger arrived in Galveston, TX and informed the enslaved African Americans of their freedom and the end of the Civil War. Learn more about Juneteenth at the National Museum of African American History & Culture!
https://nmaahc.si.edu/events/juneteenth

Todos los campos de juego permanecerán cerrados por ahora- evaluaremos la apertura de los campos de juego después del 1 de Junio.

Phase I of Governor Laura Kelly's plan will go into effect on Monday, May 4. The current Stay at Home Order for the state will remain in effect over the weekend. Riley County will issue local guidance tomorrow after collaborating with Pottawatomie County, Kansas, Geary County Emergency Management, the Recovery Task Force, and the Clinical Task Force. post_text: Important information for meals!
shared_text:
USD 383 Child Nutrition Department
April 1 at 5:36 PM ·

IMPORTANT INFORMATION!!!!!

Beginning on Thursday April 2nd we will be allowing parents or guardians to pick up a meal permit for their children’s meals.

This meal permit will allow a parent to pick up the number of meals on your permit without your children needing to be in the car. Beginning April 2nd the number given on the permit will be based on the number of children in the vehicle when the permit is issued.

This means in order for all children in your household to receive a meal you must bring all of them on the day you pick up your permit. Once you receive your permit then you will just need to have the permit hanging on your rear view mirror in order to receive meals.

You are still welcome to bring your children with you as we do enjoy seeing them.

We are hoping by allowing families to pick up meals without children will help limit the risk of exposure for both families and our staff.

post_text: Be Smart Friends
shared_text:
RileyCountyPD
March 30 at 4:04 PM ·

A dangerous scam is targeting our most vulnerable residents.

Scammers are calling people claiming they are with the IRS and have stimulus money available to give to you. The only thing you need to do is provide your account information and they will quickly deposit it into your account.

DO NOT FALL FOR IT!

This is a Scam.

Do not give your personal or financial information to anyone over the phone. If you are receiving a check from the IRS, they have your information from your most recent tax return. If you do not believe they have your information, contact them directly.

This is a hard time financially for a lot of people right now. We need your help sharing this message with friends, family and neighbors so they do not lose their hard-earned money to scammers.

shared_text:
USD 383 Child Nutrition Department
March 31 at 7:36 PM ·

We have received many "thank you's" from parents and the community. THANK YOU, these two words mean more than anything especially in times like these.

It becomes difficult to continue to smile when we are criticized or when being yelled at during lunch service. To those of you who seem to always find the negative, try to remember that this is all new to us and we are adapting every day to make things run smoother than the day before.

We served 400 more today then yesterday and are diligently working to make sure every child receives a meal. Please be patient with us as we navigate these unfamiliar times. See you tomorrow!

We are aware of the third person in Riley County testing positive for COVID-19 and his relationship with an employee at Marlatt Elementary School. That employee has not been at the school for 6 days and currently does not have any symptoms.

We have been in contact with the Riley County Health Department and they cleared us to continue with student pick up of belongings. According to the CDC, the COVID-19 virus is detectable on cardboard for up to 24 hours and plastic and steel for up to 72 hours. Riley County Health Department has also asked us to contact Marlatt staff members that could have been in contact with that employee and ask them to self-monitor and watch for any symptoms.

If you do not feel comfortable picking up student belongings at this time, please contact your child's school to make alternative arrangements.As always, the safety and health of our staff, students and community members are a priority.

CDC.GOV
COVID-19: What Older Adults Need To Know

CDC
March 10 at 8:25 PM ·

If you are an older adult or have a severe chronic medical condition, prepare in advance for the possibility of a COVID-19 outbreak in your community. Take extra measures to put distance between yourself and other people to reduce your risk of being exposed:

• Stay home as much as possible
• Have enough household items and groceries on hand if you need to stay home
• Monitor your health and keep in touch with your doctor

Learn how to be prepared if COVID-19 starts spreading in your community: http://bit.ly/2TDQVQm

post_text:
Interested in politics?

Did you know census data is used to reapportion the U.S. House of Representatives–it will determine how many seats the state of Kansas gets (currently we have 4). Furthermore, census data is used to redraw the boundaries of state legislative, local, and school districts, adapting to changes in population.

In terms of politics, taking the census is just as important as voting–both a civic duty of each resident. Learn more today at kansascaounts.org.

National, state and local governments are not the only entities who use census data.

Residents use census data to support community initiatives such as legislation, quality-of-life and consumer advocacy. Real estate developers and city planners use census data to plan for housing and to improve neighborhoods. Businesses use census data to determine where to build factories, offices and stores– all of which create jobs.

Find out how communities use census data at kansascounts.org.

post_text: Don’t fall for this scam!
shared_text:
RileyCountyPD
February 11 at 4:52 PM ·

EMPLOYMENT!!! INTERNSHIP OPPORTUNTITY!

^^^ This is how a new email scam started and it's targeting students. We were contacted this week by a female who received the email below. Unfortunately this is a scam to gain personal and financial information.

The scammer provides fake certification and then offers a too-good-to-be-true employment opportunity. They try to appeal to a person's empathy by stating they are helping disabled students in Australia.

Protect your information! Personal information is just as important as financial information. Do not send your drivers license or other identifying credentials to strangers. If you receive an unsolicited offer, make sure you investigate before you reply.

Is the census secure? Yes, VERY secure!

Federal law protects your individual census responses, which can only be used to produce statistics. In fact, by law, the
U.S. Census Bureau cannot share your information with immigration agencies, law enforcement agencies or allow it to be used to determine your eligibility for government benefits.

Don’t let concerns about security keep you from participating in a complete count in 2020. Learn more at KansasCounts.org. #KansasCounts #2020Census

Scam Alert -- it has come to our attention that there is an out of state company (Sportsmedia/Texas) calling local businesses asking for financial sponsorships of MHS by selling apparel, banners, and other products. This company is falsely claiming that by purchasing one of the items, that you are sponsoring a team (the most recent scams stated that you will be sponsoring MHS Basketball and/or MHS Football and that your sponsorship will be announced during every home game).

MHS is NOT working with this company. If your business has been contacted and/or has made a payment, we encourage you to contact Riley County Police Department at 785-537-2112.

If your business gets a phone call asking to financially support something at the high school or any of our schools, please contact MHS Athletic Director Mike Marsh (587-2100) or Communications Director Michele Jones (587-2000). We would be happy to talk with you to make sure it is legitimate.

On Friday, February 7, 2020, University Christian Church and Manhattan Parks and Recreation host Night to Shine, sponsored by the Tim Tebow Foundation. Night to Shine is an unforgettable prom night experience, for people with special needs, ages 14 and older. Now in its sixth year, this event has annually celebrated thousands of people with special needs all over the world on the Friday before Valentine’s Day!

For info contact zachary.bayless@cityofmhk.com or visit the Special Community Alliance Facebook page.

#NightToShine #TimTebowFoundation #StandWithUs

Here is a reminder of the set exclusion date of Dec. 2 to get your children vaccinated and/or provide records of vaccination.

According to the law of the state of Kansas, students must be up to date on immunizations and provide proof of immunizations in order to avoid exclusion from school, unless they have religious beliefs that prevent them from getting immunizations or have a doctor’s note that states student doesn’t need immunizations for medical reasons.

Riley County Health Department has vaccine clinic on Tuesday and Wednesday. You can call ahead to make an appointment to avoid long lines.

Contact your doctor or school nurse if you have questions!

post_text:
The USD 383 Board of Education will receive a recommendation during the Nov. 20 meeting to name the new USD 383 elementary school Oliver Brown Elementary School.
Oliver Brown is the namesake and a plaintiff in the landmark Brown v. Topeka Board of Education case that challenged segregation in public schools.
To read more, visit our website https://www.usd383.org/Home/Components/News/News/10056/17

shared_text:
USD 383 Child Nutrition Department
November 15, 2019 at 6:40 PM ·

Did you know the majority of our schools have Share Tables? Students may place unused, packaged items in the Share Table bins for students who have finished their breakfast or lunch, but are still hungry or thirsty. Share Tables are a way we try to help reduce food waste AND help kids who may need a little more to get them through the day!
